[0.018, "o", "\u001b[H\n\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Lineage:** It was spawned by a Zsh shell process (`/usr/bin/zsh`, PID 383680). \u001b[0m                                           \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Strings Analysis:** Running `strings` on the binary revealed several concerning indicators:\u001b[0m                               \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   **Obfuscation markers:** Strings like `enc_path`, `enc_label_c2`, `enc_label_key`, and `enc_label_path` strongly\u001b[m        \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204msuggest the binary is performing some form of encryption or encoding, likely to hide its activity or configuration (e.g., C2\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204minfrastructure).\u001b[0m                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   **Source File Reference:** It explicitly contains a reference to `obf_target.c`, which confirms it is a custom-\u001b[m         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcompiled binary specifically designed to be obfuscated.\u001b[0m                                                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   **Dynamic Linking:** It is dynamically linked, but the presence of the `enc` labels combined with standard libraries\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mlike `libc.so.6` suggests this is where the \"heavy lifting\" of the obfuscation resides.\u001b[0m                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Current State:** It is currently running in an active state but seems to have minimal file/network effects recorded *at\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mthis exact moment*. However, given the labels in the strings, it is likely designed to contact an external source once it\u001b[m       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcompletes its initial routine.\u001b[0m                                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Contextual Clues\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mI also noticed that a compilation process occurred recently:\u001b[0m                                                                    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   A sequence of `gcc`, `cc1`, `as`, `ld`, and `collect2` (PIDs 384852ŌĆō384856) was observed shortly before the target process\u001b[m  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mstarted, which is characteristic of someone compiling code (likely the `obf_target.c` file mentioned in the strings) directly\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mon the machine.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                 \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Recommendation\u001b[0m                                                                                                              \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1.  **Immediate Action:** Do you recognize the `obf_target.c` source file? If not, this is highly likely to be unauthorized\u001b[m     \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcode execution. You should consider terminating PID 384857 immediately.\u001b[0m                                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m2.  **Investigation:** I recommend inspecting the user `raul`'s shell history to see if there were commands related to\u001b[m          \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcompiling `obf_target.c` or downloading strange scripts, as that will provide the best lead on how this binary arrived on the\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204msystem.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mWould you like me to check the shell history for user `raul` to see what led to the creation of this f"]
