[0.064, "o", "\u001b[H\n\n\u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myouŌØ» \u001b[0mtry it again                                                                                                               \r\n  \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0mŌīĢ search\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153m/290367/ ┬Ę 23 effect matches ┬Ę /usr/bin/ps -ax -o pid=,ppid=,pcpu=,pmem=,command=, sh, /bin/sh -c /usr/bin/ps -\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153max -o pid=,ppid=,pcpu=,pmem=,command=\u001b[0m                                                                                           \r\n\u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshellŌØ» \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe search results clarify exactly what is happening: **PID 290367 is not a running process**, but a target that is\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mbeing aggressively polled.\u001b[0m                                                                                                      \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mNumerous shell scripts (running `sh` and `ps`) are repeatedly attempting to open `/proc/290367`. This behavior is\u001b[m               \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcharacteristic of an automated script, monitor, or rootkit checking for the existence of that specific PID to either monitor\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mit for activity or to prevent it from being identified by conventional tools.\u001b[0m                                                   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Key Observations\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Persistent Polling:** Multiple processes (`sh`, `ps`) are checking for the existence of `/proc/290367` every few seconds\u001b[m  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m(e.g., timestamps at 15:56:05, 10, 15, 20, 30, 40, etc.).\u001b[0m                                                                       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Suspicious Context:** The constant `ps` calls (e.g., `ps -ax -o pid=,ppid=,pcpu=,pmem=,command=`) suggest an attempt to\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mscrape process information across the entire system.\u001b[0m                                                                            \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **The Target:** Since the process itself does not appear in the active process summary, it is likely that the script or\u001b[m     \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mattacker is using this as a \"ghost\" PID to monitor for when something is spawned or to perform some kind of time-of-check-\u001b[m      \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mtime-of-use (TOCTOU) evasion.\u001b[0m                                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m**Important Note:** The fact that other processes (`sh`, `ps`) are specifically looking for this non-existent PID is a major\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mred flag for malicious activity or a highly intrusive monitoring script running on the system.\u001b[0m                                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mDo you have any idea what software (e.g., security tools, custom scripts) might be configured to monitor processes on this\u001b[m      \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204msystem? If not, this is definitely something we should trace to the parent of these various `sh` processes. Would you like me\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mto trace the tree of one of these `sh` processes?\u001b[0m                                                                               \r\n\u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myouŌØ» \u001b[0mgodshell inspectthis pid 384857                                                                                            \r\n  \u001b[48;"]
