[0.101, "o", "\u001b[H\n\n  \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0mŌ¢ż get_maps\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 384857 ┬Ę 25 regions ┬Ę heap ┬Ę stack ┬Ę 8 libs mapped\u001b[0m                                                          \r\n  \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0mŌÜĪ trace\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 384857 ┬Ę 9 calls ┬Ę 0 unique syscalls\u001b[0m                                                                          \r\n\u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshellŌØ» \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe investigation of **PID 384857** (`/tmp/obf_target`) confirms it is a highly suspicious, potentially malicious\u001b[m     \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mprocess.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                        \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Findings\u001b[0m                                                                                                                    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Persistent & Idle:** The `strace` output shows the process is in a `restart_syscall` state, meaning it is currently\u001b[m       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mblocked or waiting on a system callŌĆöcommonly used by backdoors to stay quiet (dormant) until a specific trigger, time, or\u001b[m       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mcommand is received.\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Memory Footprint:** The memory map shows it is quite small (minimal heap, only standard linked libraries), which is\u001b[m       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mexpected for a small, obfuscated, custom tool.\u001b[0m                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Evasion Technique:** The fact that it is a custom binary residing in `/tmp/` and its `strace` output shows no diagnostic\u001b[m  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mactivity (like I/O or network attempts) strongly implies that it spends most of its time in a sleeping or waiting state to\u001b[m      \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mavoid detection.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Context:** As previously established, this process was compiled on the system recently (`gcc` activity).\u001b[0m                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Conclusion\u001b[0m                                                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThis process is **highly suspicious**. Since it does not appear to be performing any benign work and is intentionally\u001b[m           \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mobfuscated, it should be treated as a threat.\u001b[0m                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Immediate Recommendations\u001b[0m                                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1.  **Terminate the process:** You should kill PID 384857.\u001b[0m                                                                      \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m2.  **Delete the binary:** Remove `/tmp/obf_target`.\u001b[0m                                                                            \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m3.  **Investigate persistent entry points:** Since it was compiled on-system, I strongly advise we look at the shell history\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mof user `raul` (or whoever owns this process) to see who invoked the compilation commands. This will help you find the source\u001b[m   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mof the malicious script or backdoor.\u001b[0m                 "]
