[0.083, "o", "\u001b[H\n\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mconfiguration from? This will likely reveal the location of the encrypted source file.\u001b[0m                                          \r\n\u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myouŌØ» \u001b[0mead it better                                                                                                              \r\n  \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0mŌ¼Ī read_memory\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 384857 @ 0x55f3fe810000 ┬Ę 20297 bytes ┬Ę 98% printable\u001b[0m                                                    \r\n\u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshellŌØ» \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThis dump exposes the configuration of the malicious agent in plaintext within its heap.\u001b[0m                              \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Critical Findings\u001b[0m                                                                                                           \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Target File:** The string `\"/etc/shadow\"` is present in the configuration. This is explosive. The process is\u001b[m              \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mspecifically targeting the Linux password shadow file, which contains encrypted user passwords.\u001b[0m                                 \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Key/C2 Details:**\u001b[0m                                                                                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   `C2 server : `\u001b[0m                                                                                                          \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   `beacon key: `\u001b[0m                                                                                                          \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m    *   `xK9#mP2$vL5@nQ8` (This appears to be the actual beacon key or an obfuscated credential).\u001b[0m                               \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m*   **Operational Status:** The process has moved past initialization (confirmed by `config decoded.`) and is currently\u001b[m         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mconfigured to target sensitive system files for exfiltration to a command-and-control server.\u001b[0m                                   \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Assessment\u001b[0m                                                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThis process is confirmed to be an **active, credential-stealing malware**. It is not just \"suspicious\"ŌĆöit is actively\u001b[m          \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mpreparing to exfiltrate password data from your system.\u001b[0m                                                                         \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m### Immediate Action Plan\u001b[0m                                                                                                       \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1.  **Stop the process:** Immediately terminate PID 384857.\u001b[0m                                                                     \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m2.  **Isolate:** If this is a networked machine, consider disconnecting it from the network immediately until you can verify\u001b[m    \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mthe extent of the exfiltration.\u001b[0m                                                                                                 \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m3.  **Containment:** The binary `/tmp/obf_target` **must be deleted**.\u001b[0m                                                          \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204m4.  **Forensics:** Since it targeted `/etc/shadow`, you **must** consider the credentials on this system compromised. You will\u001b[m  \r\n\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mneed to rotate all user passwords and privileged secrets once the system is cleaned.\u001b[0m                                            \r\n\u001b[3"]
